# Interface Contract Integrity

If a function needs a method that the contract interface doesn't declare, **add it to the interface**. Never extend the interface inline at the call site, especially with optional (`?`) methods.

## Why

Inline contract extensions silently bypass `implements`-clause checking. Any class that "implements" the base interface compiles cleanly even if it never wires the new method, and the runtime guard (`if (!manager.foo) return;`) hides the gap. Result: code that *appears* to do something ships doing nothing.

## Pattern to Avoid

```typescript
// BAD — three production entity types silently no-oped a reconciler this way
function reconcile<T>(
   manager: IFederatedEntityManager<T> & { findUnreplicated?: (id: string, n: number) => Promise<T[]> },
) {
   if (!manager.findUnreplicated) return; // any implementer can omit; tsc never complains
   const rows = await manager.findUnreplicated(...);
}
```

Two failures stack here:
1. Inline anonymous shape on a parameter type — also violates `typescript-named-types.mdc`.
2. Optional contract method — `implements IFederatedEntityManager<T>` doesn't see the extension, so missing implementations compile.

## Correct Pattern

```typescript
// GOOD — promote the method to the interface, force every implementer to wire it
export type IFederatedEntityManager<T> = {
   // ...existing required methods...
   findUnreplicated: (jurisdiction_id: string, limit: number) => Promise<T[]>;
};

function reconcile<T>(manager: IFederatedEntityManager<T>) {
   const rows = await manager.findUnreplicated(...); // contract guarantees it
}
```

Now tsc refuses to compile any class that claims `implements IFederatedEntityManager<T>` without a real `findUnreplicated`.

## Rules

- New behavior on a typed contract → goes on the contract, not the call site.
- Optional contract methods (`foo?: ...`) are forbidden unless absence is a deliberate, documented variation point with a clear default. Even then, prefer required + a no-op default implementation on a base class.
- If you only need the new behavior on *one* implementer, that's a sign the method belongs as a public method on that concrete class, not on a contract — narrow the parameter type to the concrete class instead of widening the interface.

